{"id": "9ae1af0e2803", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn truncate_str(s: &str, n: usize) -> String {\n    s.chars().take(n).collect()\n}", "question": "Why use chars().take instead of byte slicing &s[..n]?", "options": ["Byte slicing is faster always", "Byte slicing requires indices to fall on UTF-8 character boundaries; otherwise panic", "chars().take is more readable", "collect is not safe"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "utf8-char-boundary", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "String slicing requires indices to fall on UTF-8 character boundaries; slicing inside a multi-byte char panics. Use s.char_indices() or s.chars().take(n) for char-safe truncation.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "0cbb32421e30", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn sum_empty(v: Vec<i32>) -> i32 {\n    v.into_iter().reduce(|a, b| a + b).unwrap()\n}", "question": "What edge case panics?", "options": ["Vec contains negative numbers", "Vec is empty - reduce returns None", "Sum overflows i32", "Vec contains zero"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "empty-iter-fold", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Iterator::reduce returns None for empty iterators since there is no initial value. Use .fold(0, |a, b| a+b) or .sum() for a safe default. The principle is reduce on empty iterator yields None.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "a12b999fd6f6", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn f64_equal(a: f64, b: f64) -> bool {\n    a == b\n}", "question": "What edge case makes this unreliable?", "options": ["NaN is never equal to NaN, even itself", "Negative zero equals positive zero", "Floats compare bitwise", "Infinity compares as NaN"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "f64-NaN-eq", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "IEEE 754 specifies that NaN != NaN, so f64::NAN == f64::NAN is false. This violates reflexivity, which is why f64 implements PartialEq but not Eq.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "74671a718808", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn count_chars(s: &str) -> usize {\n    s.len()\n}", "question": "What is misleading about this function name?", "options": ["len() returns byte count, not character count", "len() is O(n) - slow", "len() returns characters correctly", "len() includes a trailing null"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "string-len-bytes", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "str::len() returns the number of bytes in UTF-8 encoding, not Unicode scalar values (chars). For e-acute (2 bytes) or crab emoji (4 bytes), this differs from .chars().count().", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "394f7b5b7ef2", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn parse_num(s: &str) -> i32 {\n    s.parse::<i32>().expect(\"should parse\")\n}", "question": "Which input causes a panic?", "options": ["empty string", "very large number causing overflow", "negative number", "zero"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "parse-int-overflow", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "str::parse::<i32>() returns Err(PosOverflow) when the value exceeds i32::MAX, and .expect() panics on Err. The principle is integer parsing fails on overflow, not just on bad chars.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "c04dc6e60e1a", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn signed_abs(x: i32) -> i32 {\n    x.abs()\n}", "question": "What edge case causes a panic in debug or returns a negative in release?", "options": ["x is zero", "x is i32::MIN - cannot be represented as positive", "x is positive", "x is -1"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "signed-overflow", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "i32::MIN.abs() overflows because i32::MIN is -2147483648 but i32::MAX is 2147483647. In debug it panics; in release it wraps to i32::MIN. Use wrapping_abs or checked_abs.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "00c32f6c664b", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn first_char_byte(s: &str) -> u8 {\n    s.as_bytes()[0]\n}", "question": "What pitfall does this hide?", "options": ["First byte equals first char only for ASCII", "Always returns 0 for non-ASCII", "Panics on Unicode", "Returns char count"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "char-vs-byte", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "For multi-byte UTF-8 chars, as_bytes()[0] returns the first byte of the encoding, not the codepoint. Use s.chars().next() for a logical character. The principle is byte indexing exposes UTF-8 encoding, not chars.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "deec9e360ec6", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn from_hex(s: &str) -> u32 {\n    u32::from_str_radix(s, 16).unwrap()\n}", "question": "Besides invalid hex, what causes unwrap to panic?", "options": ["Leading 0x prefix not stripped", "Lowercase letters", "Numbers larger than u32::MAX", "All of these are valid causes"], "correct_idx": 3, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "from-str-radix", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "from_str_radix does not accept a 0x prefix (treats it as invalid digit), and overflow returns Err. Lowercase is fine. The principle is from_str_radix has strict input format and overflow checks.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "3a037ec65f8d", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn shift_left(x: u32, n: u32) -> u32 {\n    x.wrapping_shl(n)\n}", "question": "What is the difference between wrapping_shl and the << operator at large n?", "options": ["No difference", "<< panics in debug for n >= 32; wrapping_shl uses n mod 32", "wrapping_shl is undefined", "<< is removed in Rust 2021"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "shift-overflow", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Shifting by an amount >= the bit width is undefined in many languages; in Rust it panics in debug. wrapping_shl uses n mod bit-width semantics. Use checked_shl if you want explicit failure.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "bb9efe436a01", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn to_f32(x: i64) -> f32 {\n    x as f32\n}", "question": "What edge case loses information?", "options": ["Negative values", "Values above 2^24 lose precision in f32 mantissa", "Zero converts to NaN", "Conversion always panics"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "int-to-float", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "f32 has a 23-bit mantissa, so integers above 2^24 cannot be exactly represented. The as cast rounds silently. The principle is integer-to-float casts lose precision beyond mantissa range.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "af1c70c587b7", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn fold_max(v: &[i32]) -> i32 {\n    v.iter().fold(i32::MIN, |a, &b| a.max(b))\n}", "question": "What is the edge-case behavior when v is empty?", "options": ["Panics", "Returns i32::MIN - the init value", "Returns 0", "Returns undefined garbage"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "fold-empty", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "fold with i32::MIN as init returns the init value for an empty iterator, which is misleading as a max. Better to use .iter().max() returning Option. The principle is fold over empty iter returns the init value.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "e619d05ecb94", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn cast_truncate(x: i64) -> i8 {\n    x as i8\n}", "question": "What happens for cast_truncate(300)?", "options": ["Returns 127 (saturated)", "Returns 44 (truncates low 8 bits, signed)", "Panics with overflow", "Compile-time error"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "as-truncate", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "as casts between integer types truncate by taking the low N bits and reinterpreting as the target signedness; no panic, no saturation. 300 mod 256 = 44. Use TryFrom for checked conversion.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "9ceca76a816f", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn modulo(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 {\n    a % b\n}", "question": "Which case panics?", "options": ["a is negative", "b is zero", "Result is negative", "a equals b"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "mod-zero", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "The remainder operator % panics on b == 0 for integers, just like /. Additionally, i32::MIN % -1 is handled (returns 0). The principle is integer remainder by zero panics.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "4a4be37a2766", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn rev_string(s: &str) -> String {\n    s.chars().rev().collect()\n}", "question": "What Unicode edge case does this mishandle?", "options": ["ASCII characters", "Combining diacritics (grapheme clusters split)", "Empty strings", "All Latin characters"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "grapheme-cluster", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "chars() iterates Unicode scalar values, but a grapheme cluster like e plus combining acute would reverse to acute-then-e, producing wrong output. Use the unicode-segmentation crate. The principle is chars are scalar values, not grapheme clusters.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "ceebb60a2098", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn read_u32(buf: &[u8]) -> u32 {\n    let arr: [u8; 4] = [buf[0], buf[1], buf[2], buf[3]];\n    u32::from_le_bytes(arr)\n}", "question": "What edge case is unsafe?", "options": ["Endianness mismatch", "Buffer length < 4 panics on indexing", "u32 alignment", "Negative bytes"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "slice-oob", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Indexing buf[0..3] panics if the buffer has fewer than 4 bytes. Use buf.get(..4) or try_into() on a 4-byte slice for safe error handling. The principle is slice indexing panics on OOB.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "93f7000a6f48", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn avg(v: &[u32]) -> u32 {\n    let s: u32 = v.iter().sum();\n    s / v.len() as u32\n}", "question": "What two edge cases break this?", "options": ["Empty slice (div-by-zero) and sum overflow", "Only negative values", "Slice with one element", "Unsorted slice"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "div-zero-empty", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "An empty slice causes division by zero (panic), and summing many large u32s can overflow. Use checked_add/checked_div or fold to u64. The principle is aggregates must handle empty input and accumulator overflow.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "030275ff6906", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn negate(x: u32) -> u32 {\n    0u32.wrapping_sub(x)\n}", "question": "Why use wrapping_sub instead of 0 - x?", "options": ["No difference", "Unsigned subtraction that goes below 0 panics in debug; wrapping_sub explicitly wraps", "wrapping_sub is slower", "0 - x is invalid syntax"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "unsigned-underflow", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Unsigned subtraction that goes below 0 panics in debug and wraps in release. wrapping_sub makes the wrapping intent explicit. The principle is unsigned underflow has same semantics as overflow.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "89abd065980e", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn last<T: Clone>(v: &[T]) -> Option<T> {\n    v.last().cloned()\n}", "question": "Why is this version safe vs v[v.len()-1].clone()?", "options": ["Clone is cheaper", "v.last() returns None on empty slice; v.len()-1 underflows usize on empty", "No difference", "v.last is deprecated"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "usize-underflow", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "For an empty slice, v.len() == 0, and 0usize - 1 underflows (panics debug, wraps to usize::MAX, then panics on OOB index). v.last().cloned() avoids the arithmetic. The principle is usize underflow on empty container length arithmetic.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "9d8c414025ef", "lang": "rust", "code": "use std::collections::HashMap;\npub fn get_or_zero(m: &HashMap<String, i32>, k: &str) -> i32 {\n    m.get(k).copied().unwrap_or(0)\n}", "question": "Why use unwrap_or(0) instead of expect?", "options": ["Cleaner syntax", "Missing key would panic with expect; unwrap_or provides a default", "No difference", "expect is removed"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "expect-vs-unwrap-or", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "HashMap::get returns Option<&V>; expect on None panics. .copied().unwrap_or(0) provides a default. The principle is expect on Option::None panics like unwrap.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "fd3336ee1761", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn parse_or_default(s: &str) -> u8 {\n    s.parse::<u8>().unwrap_or(0)\n}", "question": "Why parse directly to u8 instead of parsing u32 then casting?", "options": ["Faster", "Parsing u32 then as u8 silently truncates large values; parsing to u8 rejects them", "Same behavior", "u32 cannot parse"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "as-cast-truncate", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "If you parse 300 as u32 (success) then cast as u8, you get 44. Parsing directly to u8 returns Err for 300. Use the narrowest type that fits your domain. The principle is as cast on integer truncates silently.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "fcadca8769b0", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn slice_mid(s: &str) -> &str {\n    let mid = s.len() / 2;\n    if s.is_char_boundary(mid) {\n        &s[..mid]\n    } else {\n        s\n    }\n}", "question": "Why the is_char_boundary check?", "options": ["Performance", "Byte length / 2 may not be a char boundary; slicing inside a multi-byte char panics", "Cosmetic", "Required by borrow checker"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "char-boundary", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "For multi-byte strings, mid may fall between bytes of a single char. Slicing then panics. is_char_boundary guards against that. The principle is byte length / 2 is not guaranteed to be a char boundary.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "a393bb40e776", "lang": "rust", "code": "use std::sync::Mutex;\npub struct Counter { m: Mutex<i32> }\nimpl Counter {\n    pub fn inc(&self) {\n        let mut g = self.m.lock().unwrap();\n        *g += 1;\n    }\n}", "question": "When can lock().unwrap() panic?", "options": ["Never - Mutex never fails", "If another thread panicked while holding the lock (PoisonError)", "On deadlock", "On uncontended access"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "mutex-poison", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Rust Mutex::lock returns Result<MutexGuard, PoisonError> where the error indicates another thread panicked while holding the lock. Use .lock().unwrap_or_else(|e| e.into_inner()) to recover. The principle is Mutex poisoning on panicking holder.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "6373188f33e3", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn concat_strings(parts: &[&str]) -> String {\n    let cap: usize = parts.iter().map(|s| s.len()).sum();\n    let mut r = String::with_capacity(cap);\n    for p in parts { r.push_str(p); }\n    r\n}", "question": "Why preallocate with_capacity?", "options": ["Avoid repeated reallocation as the string grows", "Compile-time requirement", "Decorative", "Required by borrow checker"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "string-prealloc", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Building a string with repeated push_str/concat may reallocate; with_capacity pre-sizes the buffer so push_str is amortized O(1). The principle is repeated string concatenation is quadratic without preallocation.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "2b5f7ee338db", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn find_index(v: &[i32], target: i32) -> Option<usize> {\n    v.iter().position(|&x| x == target)\n}", "question": "Why return Option instead of unwrapping inside?", "options": ["Cleaner", "Caller can decide how to handle absence; unwrap inside would panic on missing", "Required by trait", "No reason"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "option-vs-panic", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "position returns None when no element matches. Propagating Option lets the caller decide how to handle absence. The principle is searching may produce None; do not unwrap blindly.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "6dff2f228ec1", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn pop_two<T>(v: &mut Vec<T>) -> Option<(T, T)> {\n    let b = v.pop()?;\n    let a = v.pop()?;\n    Some((a, b))\n}", "question": "Why is the order (a, b) instead of (pop1, pop2)?", "options": ["Pop removes from the end; reversing preserves push order", "No reason", "Compile error otherwise", "Required by Vec contract"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "pop-order", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Vec::pop removes from the end, so the first element popped is the last pushed. Reversing inside the tuple preserves logical order. The principle is pop on empty Vec yields None; using ? propagates correctly.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "910c0e8864f5", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn sum_to_n(n: u32) -> u64 {\n    (n as u64) * ((n as u64) + 1) / 2\n}", "question": "Why is the formula computed in u64?", "options": ["No reason", "u32 multiplication can overflow; u64 has more headroom", "Required syntax", "Floating point precision"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "overflow-wider", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "For large n, n * (n+1) can exceed u32::MAX. Casting to u64 first avoids overflow. The closed form is also O(1) vs O(n). The principle is replace loops with closed forms and check overflow.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "4b7cba25be42", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn dedup_sorted(v: &mut Vec<i32>) {\n    v.sort();\n    v.dedup();\n}", "question": "Why sort before dedup?", "options": ["dedup needs sorted input to remove all duplicates", "dedup requires sort", "sort is decorative", "Required by trait bound"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "dedup-precondition", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Vec::dedup only removes consecutive duplicates. Sorting first ensures equal elements are adjacent. The principle is dedup operates on adjacent equality only.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "c40b540eb5a4", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn read_line_first_word(s: &str) -> Option<&str> {\n    s.split_whitespace().next()\n}", "question": "Why return Option?", "options": ["Cleaner", "Empty or whitespace-only input yields no tokens, so next() may be None", "Required syntax", "No reason"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "split-empty", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "split_whitespace skips whitespace and yields tokens; an empty or whitespace-only string produces no tokens. Returning Option propagates the absence cleanly. The principle is split_whitespace can yield empty iterator.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "d9c17e4d474d", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn clamp_u8(x: i32) -> u8 {\n    x.clamp(0, 255) as u8\n}", "question": "Why clamp before as cast?", "options": ["Required syntax", "as u8 truncates: -1 as u8 = 255, 256 as u8 = 0; clamp first preserves semantics", "Decorative", "Faster"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "clamp-vs-as", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "as u8 truncates: negative or >255 silently wraps. Clamping first ensures the value lies in 0..=255 before truncation. The principle is as cast does not clamp; it truncates/wraps.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "896da88e4964", "lang": "rust", "code": "use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicUsize, Ordering};\npub struct Counter(AtomicUsize);\nimpl Counter {\n    pub fn inc(&self) -> usize {\n        self.0.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed) + 1\n    }\n}", "question": "Why use fetch_add instead of separate load/store?", "options": ["fetch_add is atomic RMW; load+store can be interleaved by another thread causing lost updates", "No difference", "Required by AtomicUsize", "Faster"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "atomic-rmw", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "Load followed by store is two operations; another thread can read the same value and increment, causing lost updates. fetch_add is a single atomic RMW. The principle is atomic load+store is not atomic read-modify-write.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "e050aeda6b89", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn sort_descending(v: &mut Vec<f64>) {\n    v.sort_by(|a, b| b.total_cmp(a));\n}", "question": "Why use total_cmp instead of partial_cmp().unwrap()?", "options": ["partial_cmp returns None for NaN; total_cmp defines a total order", "No difference", "total_cmp is faster", "partial_cmp does not exist for f64"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "f64-total-cmp", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "f64::partial_cmp returns None for NaN comparisons (since NaN is unordered). Unwrapping panics. total_cmp (Rust 1.62+) defines a total order on floats. The principle is NaN has no defined ordering; partial_cmp returns None.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "fa794b766977", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn longest<'a>(a: &'a str, b: &'a str) -> &'a str {\n    if a.len() > b.len() { a } else { b }\n}", "question": "Why is the lifetime 'a on both inputs?", "options": ["The returned reference can come from either input; the shared lifetime ties them", "Decorative", "Required by trait", "Compiler infers it"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "lifetime-bound", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "The function may return either a or b, so the output lifetime must cover both. Using a single lifetime 'a on both inputs and the output expresses this correctly. The principle is output lifetime must cover all possible returned inputs.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "7044395f815a", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn copy_slice(src: &[u8], dst: &mut [u8]) -> bool {\n    if src.len() != dst.len() { return false; }\n    dst.copy_from_slice(src);\n    true\n}", "question": "Why check lengths before copy_from_slice?", "options": ["copy_from_slice panics if lengths differ", "Required by Rust", "Cosmetic", "Faster"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "copy-len-match", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "copy_from_slice requires src.len() == dst.len() and panics otherwise. Returning false on mismatch is a defensive design. The principle is copy_from_slice requires exact length match.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "06483a854602", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn rectangle_area(w: u32, h: u32) -> u64 {\n    (w as u64) * (h as u64)\n}", "question": "Why compute the product in u64?", "options": ["u32 multiplication can overflow for large w, h; widening prevents that", "No reason", "Required by trait", "Faster"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "widen-before-mul", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "For w, h near u32::MAX, the product exceeds u32::MAX and wraps in release (panics in debug). Casting to u64 first prevents overflow. The principle is widen narrow types before multiplication when the product can be large.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "ba641047ff7e", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn split_csv(line: &str) -> Vec<&str> {\n    line.split(',').map(|s| s.trim()).collect()\n}", "question": "What edge case is unhandled?", "options": ["Quoted fields containing commas are split incorrectly", "Empty lines", "Unicode chars", "Tab separators"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "csv-quoting", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Naive split on comma does not respect CSV quoting rules where a comma inside double-quoted fields is part of the field. Use a proper CSV parser for real CSV. The principle is delimiter-split parsers do not handle escape/quote semantics.", "sources": ["RFC-4180"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "4de5db5ba85a", "lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn percent(x: u32, total: u32) -> u32 {\n    if total == 0 { return 0; }\n    (x as u64 * 100 / total as u64) as u32\n}", "question": "Why widen to u64 in the intermediate?", "options": ["x * 100 can overflow u32 even when the final result fits", "Required syntax", "Decorative", "Faster"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "intermediate-overflow", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "For x near u32::MAX, x * 100 overflows u32. Widening the intermediate prevents this. The final divide brings the result back in range. The principle is intermediate overflow can occur even if the final value fits.", "sources": ["Rust-Reference"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "f5570c66e880", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT COUNT(*) AS total, COUNT(email) AS with_email\nFROM users\nWHERE created_at > '2024-01-01';", "question": "What is the key difference between COUNT(*) and COUNT(email)?", "options": ["They always return the same value", "COUNT(email) excludes rows where email IS NULL", "COUNT(*) excludes NULL primary keys", "COUNT(email) is faster because it uses an index"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "count-star-vs-col", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "COUNT(*) counts all rows regardless of NULLs, while COUNT(column) counts only rows where that column IS NOT NULL. This is a fundamental NULL-handling rule in SQL aggregates - NULLs are skipped by column-based counts.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "630c4282e545", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, name\nFROM products\nWHERE category != 'electronics';", "question": "What happens to rows where category IS NULL?", "options": ["They are returned because NULL != 'electronics'", "They are excluded because NULL comparisons yield UNKNOWN", "They cause a runtime error", "They are returned with category replaced by empty string"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "null-where-equal", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "NULL is not a value - any comparison with NULL (including !=) yields UNKNOWN, not TRUE, so WHERE filters them out. To include NULLs you must add OR category IS NULL explicitly.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "05f8e6afb54f", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT user_id, SUM(amount) / NULLIF(COUNT(orders), 0) AS avg_order\nFROM order_summary\nGROUP BY user_id;", "question": "Why use NULLIF(COUNT(orders), 0) in the divisor?", "options": ["Performance", "To guard against division by zero by producing NULL instead of an error", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "div-by-zero-nullif", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "NULLIF returns NULL when the divisor is 0, and division by NULL yields NULL rather than raising. This is a standard defensive SQL idiom for ratios. The principle is guard division denominators with NULLIF.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "3bc6bccc11f3", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT *\nFROM events\nWHERE event_date >= '2024-01-01'\n  AND event_date <  '2024-02-01';", "question": "Why use half-open range instead of BETWEEN '2024-01-01' AND '2024-01-31'?", "options": ["Performance", "BETWEEN is inclusive and excludes timestamps after midnight on Jan 31; half-open is safer", "BETWEEN is deprecated", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "between-edge", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "BETWEEN is inclusive but '2024-01-31' coerces to '2024-01-31 00:00:00', so events later on Jan 31 are excluded. Half-open ranges (>= start, < next_period) handle timestamp granularity cleanly.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "4f09e0bc7083", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT user_id\nFROM orders\nWHERE EXISTS (\n  SELECT 1 FROM allowed_statuses a WHERE a.status = orders.status\n);", "question": "Why EXISTS instead of IN here?", "options": ["Same thing", "EXISTS handles NULLs in the subquery without surprising empty results", "IN is deprecated", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "in-vs-exists-null", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "NOT IN with a NULL in the subquery evaluates to UNKNOWN for every row, filtering them all out. Even IN can have surprises with NULL members. EXISTS is generally safer with nullable subqueries.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "6b7b2fd00bbe", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT product_id\nFROM products\nWHERE NOT EXISTS (\n  SELECT 1 FROM discontinued d WHERE d.product_id = products.product_id\n);", "question": "Why NOT EXISTS instead of NOT IN?", "options": ["NOT IN with a NULL in the list yields no rows; NOT EXISTS is NULL-safe", "Performance", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "not-in-null", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "NOT IN with a NULL in the subquery returns no rows because every comparison against NULL is UNKNOWN. NOT EXISTS uses set membership semantics that handle NULLs naturally.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "fae406b473e0", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT department, AVG(salary) AS avg_sal\nFROM employees\nGROUP BY department\nHAVING AVG(salary) > 50000;", "question": "How does AVG treat rows where salary IS NULL?", "options": ["Treated as 0", "Skipped - AVG ignores NULLs", "Causes AVG to return NULL", "Query fails"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "null-aggregate", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "AVG (like SUM, MAX, MIN) ignores NULL inputs and averages only non-NULL values. If ALL values in a group are NULL, AVG returns NULL - not zero. This is a distinct edge case.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "eb9a7aa39844", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, total\nFROM invoices\nWHERE total > 100\nORDER BY created_at, id;", "question": "Why include id as a secondary sort key?", "options": ["Performance", "To produce deterministic ordering when created_at has duplicates", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "sort-tiebreak", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "SQL does not guarantee a stable sort for tied ORDER BY keys. A tiebreaker like id ensures deterministic ordering across executions, essential for paginated queries.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "bc761477e2f9", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id\nFROM logs\nWHERE created_at >= date_trunc('day', NOW() AT TIME ZONE 'UTC');", "question": "Why explicitly convert to UTC?", "options": ["Performance", "date_trunc uses session TimeZone; UTC pin makes day boundary deterministic", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "date-trunc-tz", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "date_trunc on a timestamptz uses the session TimeZone to determine the day boundary. Pinning to UTC makes the boundary deterministic across deployments.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "126ce7d41c26", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT user_id, MAX(score) AS best\nFROM game_scores\nGROUP BY user_id;", "question": "Why not add DISTINCT in front of user_id here?", "options": ["GROUP BY already produces unique user_id rows; DISTINCT is redundant", "DISTINCT is required", "Performance", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "distinct-redundant", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "GROUP BY already guarantees each user_id appears once in the result, so DISTINCT is superfluous and may add a sort/hash step. Choose one mechanism per query.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "a7f2da048b18", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT user_id, COUNT(*) AS n\nFROM orders\nWHERE country IS NULL\nGROUP BY user_id;", "question": "Why is the IS NULL filter in WHERE not HAVING?", "options": ["WHERE runs before grouping; per-row filters belong there for index use", "No difference", "HAVING does not support IS NULL", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "having-vs-where", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "HAVING can only reference grouped columns or aggregate expressions. Per-row filters belong in WHERE, which runs before grouping and can use indexes.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "5861901f78a2", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT order_id\nFROM orders\nWHERE order_id = ANY ('{}'::int[]);", "question": "What does this return for an empty array?", "options": ["All rows", "No rows", "Syntax error", "Random rows"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "empty-array-any", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "= ANY (empty array) is FALSE for every row, returning no rows. This is the safe way to handle dynamic IN lists when the list may be empty, as opposed to literal IN () which is a syntax error.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "600669169129", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT u.id, COALESCE(o.total, 0) AS total\nFROM users u\nLEFT JOIN LATERAL (\n  SELECT total FROM orders WHERE user_id = u.id ORDER BY created_at DESC LIMIT 1\n) o ON true;", "question": "Why LEFT JOIN LATERAL instead of CROSS JOIN LATERAL?", "options": ["LEFT preserves users with no orders by padding o columns with NULL", "Performance", "Same thing", "CROSS is deprecated"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "left-lateral", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "LEFT JOIN LATERAL preserves the left row even when the lateral subquery returns no rows, padding the right side with NULLs. CROSS JOIN LATERAL would drop users without orders.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "1a6f8e6397fe", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT data->'name' AS name_json\nFROM events\nWHERE data ? 'name';", "question": "Why use ? operator vs checking data->>'name' IS NOT NULL?", "options": ["? distinguishes missing key from JSON null; the other conflates them", "No difference", "? is faster", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "json-null-vs-missing", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "The ->> operator returns SQL NULL both when the key is missing and when its JSON value is null. The ? operator (jsonb_exists) tests key presence regardless of value.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "5174104e2881", "lang": "sql", "code": "CREATE TABLE accounts (\n  id BIGSERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  balance BIGINT NOT NULL\n);", "question": "Why BIGINT instead of INTEGER for balance?", "options": ["INTEGER cannot be NOT NULL", "INTEGER overflows above ~2.1B; large monetary sums need BIGINT or NUMERIC", "INTEGER is slower", "INTEGER does not allow negatives"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "integer-overflow", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "PostgreSQL INTEGER is signed 32-bit with max 2,147,483,647 - easy to overflow for cents-based currency totals. BIGINT or NUMERIC avoid silent overflow.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "860d59702781", "lang": "sql", "code": "CREATE TABLE events (\n  id BIGSERIAL,\n  occurred_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL\n);", "question": "Why TIMESTAMPTZ instead of TIMESTAMP?", "options": ["More storage", "TIMESTAMPTZ normalizes to UTC on input; TIMESTAMP without TZ has ambiguous wall-clock semantics", "TIMESTAMP is deprecated", "No difference"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "timestamptz", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "TIMESTAMP WITHOUT TIME ZONE stores a wall clock with no offset, so the same literal means different instants for different clients. TIMESTAMPTZ normalizes to UTC, avoiding ambiguity.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "1b5c6a56b4fc", "lang": "sql", "code": "CREATE TABLE codes (\n  code TEXT NOT NULL\n);", "question": "Why TEXT instead of VARCHAR(10)?", "options": ["TEXT is unlimited; VARCHAR(10) silently truncates", "TEXT and VARCHAR(10) behave the same except for the length cap; choose based on whether you need a hard limit", "TEXT is deprecated", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "text-vs-varchar", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "PostgreSQL TEXT and VARCHAR(n) are stored identically; the only difference is the length check. TEXT is preferred when no hard limit is needed; VARCHAR(n) raises an error (not truncates) on overflow.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "bbcc60376aed", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, name\nFROM users\nWHERE deleted_at IS NULL;", "question": "Why use IS NULL, not = NULL?", "options": ["= NULL is always UNKNOWN; IS NULL is the proper test", "No difference", "Performance", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "null-equality", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "= NULL evaluates to UNKNOWN for every row because NULL means unknown value, so WHERE filters them all out. The correct predicate is IS NULL - a frequent silent-empty-result bug.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "8f661d4b16bc", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id\nFROM users\nWHERE name = $1;", "question": "Why use $1 parameter binding?", "options": ["Performance", "Defends against SQL injection by separating data from code", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "sql-injection-param", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Bound parameters are passed separately from the SQL text so they cannot be interpreted as syntax - the principal defense against SQL injection. Hand-built quote-escaping is error-prone.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "66e093e9b005", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT *\nFROM orders\nWHERE created_at >= '2024-01-01'\n  AND created_at <  '2025-01-01';", "question": "Why this form instead of EXTRACT(YEAR FROM created_at) = 2024?", "options": ["Performance", "Wrapping created_at in a function disables a B-tree index on created_at; range predicate is sargable", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "sargable-range", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Applying EXTRACT to the indexed column makes the predicate non-sargable. Rewriting as a half-open range keeps the index usable, dramatically faster on large tables.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "02db4e27a538", "lang": "sql", "code": "BEGIN;\nSELECT balance FROM accounts WHERE id = 1 FOR UPDATE;\nUPDATE accounts SET balance = balance - 100 WHERE id = 1;\nUPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 100 WHERE id = 2;\nCOMMIT;", "question": "Why include FOR UPDATE in the SELECT?", "options": ["Performance", "Locks the row so concurrent transactions cannot read-modify-write the same balance", "Required by SQL", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "select-for-update", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "At default READ COMMITTED, two concurrent transfers can both read the original balance and overwrite each other. SELECT FOR UPDATE locks the row until commit, preventing lost updates.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "30dd71a5727f", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT u.name, o.total\nFROM users u\nINNER JOIN orders o ON u.id = o.user_id;", "question": "Why explicit INNER JOIN instead of FROM users u, orders o WHERE u.id = o.user_id?", "options": ["Performance", "Explicit JOIN separates join condition from row filters and follows ANSI SQL-92 style", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "explicit-join", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Implicit joins via FROM a, b WHERE conflate join conditions with row filters, making cardinality bugs hard to spot. Explicit INNER JOIN ... ON is the modern style.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "a5b3ab61af46", "lang": "sql", "code": "CREATE INDEX idx_users_name_trgm ON users USING gin (name gin_trgm_ops);\nSELECT id, name FROM users WHERE name ILIKE '%smith%';", "question": "Why a GIN trigram index?", "options": ["B-tree cannot index strings", "Leading-wildcard LIKE cannot use a B-tree index; trigram GIN enables substring search", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "trgm-index", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "A pattern starting with % cannot use a prefix B-tree index. The pg_trgm extension plus a GIN index on gin_trgm_ops enables fast substring search via trigram decomposition.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "a6deaf06b369", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, age\nFROM users\nWHERE age = 25;", "question": "Why compare native types directly instead of age::text = '25'?", "options": ["Performance", "Casting the column disables index use; native compare is sargable", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "unnecessary-cast", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Casting the indexed column to text turns the predicate non-sargable and forces a sequential scan. Compare native types directly so the planner can use an index on age.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "88ac4632f271", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, COALESCE(name, '') AS name_safe\nFROM users;", "question": "Why COALESCE here?", "options": ["Performance", "Defaults NULL to empty string so downstream string ops do not propagate NULL", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "coalesce-null", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "In SQL, concatenation and many string operators propagate NULL. COALESCE supplies a default so downstream logic does not silently produce NULLs.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "0d5a2f292265", "lang": "sql", "code": "INSERT INTO audit_log (user_id, action)\nVALUES (current_setting('app.user_id', true)::int, 'login');", "question": "Why the second arg true to current_setting?", "options": ["Performance", "Returns NULL when the GUC is unset instead of raising an error", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "current-setting-missing-ok", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "current_setting('foo') errors if the GUC was never SET. The missing_ok form (second arg true) returns NULL instead - safer defensive SQL.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "2df12d89811b", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT COALESCE(user_id::text, 'NULL')) AS uniques\nFROM page_views;", "question": "Why wrap user_id with COALESCE here?", "options": ["Performance", "COUNT(DISTINCT col) skips NULLs; COALESCE includes NULL as its own group", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "distinct-null", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "COUNT(DISTINCT col) ignores NULLs. Wrapping with COALESCE assigns a sentinel so NULL counts as a distinct group. Beware of sentinel collisions with real values.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "651cedd5fc31", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id\nFROM orders\nWHERE created_at < $1\nORDER BY created_at DESC\nLIMIT 10;", "question": "Why keyset pagination ($1 = last seen value) over OFFSET?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "OFFSET scans and discards skipped rows; keyset stays O(LIMIT) regardless of depth", "Required syntax", "Faster compile"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "keyset-pagination", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "OFFSET N tells PostgreSQL to fetch and throw away the first N matching rows, so cost grows linearly with N. Keyset pagination stays bounded.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "9377ad90321f", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id FROM users WHERE email ILIKE replace(replace($1, '%', '\\\\%'), '_', '\\\\_');", "question": "Why escape % and _ in the input?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "Bound parameters do not neutralize LIKE metacharacters; escape them to prevent wildcard injection", "Required syntax", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "like-escape", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "Parameter binding stops SQL injection but does not neutralize LIKE/ILIKE metacharacters - a user-supplied % can broaden a search to all rows. Escape them in the application before binding.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "5c276f9d1aba", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, EXTRACT(EPOCH FROM (now() - created_at)) AS age_sec\nFROM events;", "question": "Why is now() acceptable to use here without performance worry?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "now() (transaction_timestamp) is STABLE within a tx; planner can use indexes on created_at", "Required syntax", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "function-volatility", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "now() is STABLE within a transaction - it returns the same value for every row, so the planner can compute it once and use indexes on created_at. clock_timestamp() is VOLATILE.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "94953cd11000", "lang": "sql", "code": "BEGIN;\nUPDATE accounts SET balance = balance + 50 WHERE id = 1;\nCOMMIT;", "question": "What is the safety improvement here vs UPDATE without WHERE?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "WHERE clause prevents accidentally updating every row in the table", "Required syntax", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "missing-where", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Without WHERE, the UPDATE touches every row - a catastrophic mistake. Always include WHERE (and consider running in a transaction with BEGIN; ... ROLLBACK; first for verification).", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "32207e072137", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, total\nFROM orders\nWHERE total = 100.0::numeric;", "question": "Why cast 100.0 to numeric explicitly?", "options": ["Performance", "Avoids binary-float equality issues if total is FLOAT/DOUBLE; numeric is exact", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "float-equality", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "Binary float types cannot represent every decimal exactly. Exact comparisons should use NUMERIC, and explicit casts make intent clear.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "8de9ebff65b7", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id\nFROM users\nWHERE created_at >= CURRENT_DATE\n  AND created_at <  CURRENT_DATE + INTERVAL '1 day';", "question": "Why this form vs created_at::date = CURRENT_DATE?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "Casting the column to date is non-sargable; the range form keeps the index usable", "Required syntax", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "sargable-date", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Applying ::date to the column makes the predicate non-sargable on a B-tree over created_at. Use a half-open timestamp range instead.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "0cd1bb71bfd7", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, COALESCE(nickname, name, 'anonymous') AS display\nFROM users;", "question": "What happens if every argument is NULL?", "options": ["Error", "Returns the last argument as-is; if all are NULL, returns NULL", "Returns 'anonymous' literally", "Returns empty string"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "coalesce-cascade", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "COALESCE returns the first non-NULL value from its argument list. If every argument is NULL, the result itself is NULL. Put a non-NULL constant last as the safety net.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "689bb8a15983", "lang": "sql", "code": "INSERT INTO users (email, name) VALUES ('a@b.com', 'Alice')\nON CONFLICT (email) DO UPDATE SET name = EXCLUDED.name;", "question": "Why ON CONFLICT vs SELECT-then-INSERT?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "Atomic upsert - no race window between checking existence and inserting", "Required syntax", "Performance only"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "upsert", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "INSERT ... ON CONFLICT is a single atomic statement that uses the unique index to resolve conflicts, eliminating the race where two SELECT-then-INSERT clients both insert.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "ec8f93527339", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, name FROM users ORDER BY id LIMIT 5;", "question": "Why include ORDER BY id with LIMIT?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "LIMIT without ORDER BY returns any 5 rows the executor picks first - non-deterministic", "Required syntax", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "deterministic-limit", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "LIMIT without ORDER BY returns any rows the executor picks first - order may change with planner choices. Always pair LIMIT with explicit ORDER BY.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "b51ca103e828", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT array_agg(name) FILTER (WHERE name IS NOT NULL) AS names\nFROM users;", "question": "Why the FILTER clause?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "array_agg preserves NULLs by default; FILTER removes them", "Required syntax", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "array-agg-null", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Unlike sum/avg, array_agg keeps NULLs as actual NULL array elements. FILTER (WHERE col IS NOT NULL) drops them from the aggregate.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "675e64b248bc", "lang": "sql", "code": "CREATE INDEX idx_users_lower_email ON users (lower(email));\nSELECT id FROM users WHERE lower(email) = lower($1);", "question": "Why must the WHERE expression match the index expression?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "Functional indexes only help when the query uses the same expression", "Required syntax", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "functional-index-match", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "A functional index on lower(email) only helps when the WHERE clause contains the exact same expression. Otherwise the planner cannot use the index.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "eff716a8b81b", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, COALESCE(NULLIF(price, 0), 1) AS price_or_one\nFROM items;", "question": "What does this combination do?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "Treats 0 as if it were NULL and substitutes 1, leaving all other prices unchanged", "Returns 0 always", "Errors on 0"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "nullif-coalesce", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "NULLIF(price, 0) returns NULL when price is 0; COALESCE then substitutes 1. Together they replace a sentinel value with a default while preserving genuine NULLs path.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"id": "a9b0d9523365", "lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id FROM orders WHERE total > 0 ORDER BY total DESC LIMIT 100;", "question": "What does a code reviewer check first here?", "options": ["LIMIT", "Whether an index supports the ORDER BY total DESC scan efficiently", "Capitalization", "Trailing semicolon"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "order-index", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "ORDER BY DESC with a LIMIT benefits from an index on total. Without one, PostgreSQL sorts the entire matching set. A reviewer asks about supporting indexes.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL-Docs"], "iter": 1}
{"lang": "python", "code": "def make_multipliers(n):\n    result = []\n    for i in range(n):\n        result.append(lambda x: x * i)\n    return result\n\nfuncs = make_multipliers(4)\nprint([f(10) for f in funcs])", "question": "What is the output and why?", "options": ["[0, 10, 20, 30] because each lambda captures its own i", "[30, 30, 30, 30] due to late binding of i in closures", "[10, 20, 30, 40] because i increments at call time", "TypeError because lambda cannot capture loop variables"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "late-binding-closure", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Python closures capture variables by reference, not by value. By the time the lambdas are called, the loop has completed and i is bound to its final value 3, so every lambda multiplies by 3. The fix is to use a default argument like lambda x, i=i: x * i to capture the current value.", "sources": ["PEP 227", "Python FAQ"], "iter": 2, "id": "5ff1435c917f"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "def get_middle_third(items):\n    n = len(items)\n    start = n // 3\n    end = 2 * n // 3\n    return items[start:end+1]", "question": "What is the bug in this slicing logic?", "options": ["The slice start index is off by one", "end+1 makes the slice include an extra element, breaking the thirds invariant", "Integer division truncates incorrectly for n=9", "items[start:end] would raise IndexError"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "off-by-one-slice", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Python slices are already exclusive of the stop index, so adding +1 includes one extra element beyond the intended range. The correct slice is items[start:end] to capture the middle third cleanly. This is a classic off-by-one introduced by confusing slice semantics with inclusive ranges.", "sources": ["Python docs sequence types"], "iter": 2, "id": "d36dc1dd9cb0"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "def is_close_enough(a, b):\n    return a == b\n\nprint(is_close_enough(0.1 + 0.2, 0.3))", "question": "Why does this function return False here?", "options": ["Because == is not defined for floats in Python 3", "Because 0.1 + 0.2 is not exactly 0.3 in IEEE-754", "Because Python uses arbitrary precision for one side but not the other", "Because 0.3 is internally stored as a Decimal"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "float-equality-compare", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Floating-point arithmetic in IEEE-754 cannot exactly represent decimals like 0.1 and 0.2, so their sum differs slightly from 0.3. Direct equality comparison of floats is a well-known bug pattern. Use math.isclose with an appropriate tolerance instead.", "sources": ["math.isclose docs", "IEEE 754"], "iter": 2, "id": "ab1fd648ccd6"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "d = {'a': 1, 'b': 2, 'c': 3, 'd': 4}\nfor k in list(d):\n    if d[k] % 2 == 0:\n        del d[k]", "question": "Why does the iteration use list(d) here?", "options": ["Cosmetic", "Iterating directly over d while deleting raises RuntimeError; list(d) snapshots the keys", "del cannot be applied to dict items", "d[k] % 2 always evaluates to False for strings"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "dict-mutation-during-iter", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Python explicitly forbids resizing a dict while iterating over it and raises RuntimeError as a safety check. Iterate over list(d) or build a list of keys to delete, then delete after the loop.", "sources": ["Python docs dict iteration"], "iter": 2, "id": "0ae660a542a6"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "def consume_twice(iterable):\n    total = sum(iterable)\n    count = sum(1 for _ in iterable)\n    return total / count if count else 0\n\nresult = consume_twice(x * 2 for x in range(5))", "question": "Why does this function misbehave when given a generator?", "options": ["sum() does not accept generators", "Generators are single-pass; after the first sum() the generator is exhausted", "The division by count raises ZeroDivisionError", "Generator expressions implicitly call list()"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "iterator-exhaustion-bug", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Generators are one-shot iterators: once consumed they yield nothing. The second sum receives an empty iterable, so count is 0 and the function returns 0. Materialize to a list or accept only sequences when traversing twice.", "sources": ["PEP 255", "Python docs"], "iter": 2, "id": "76e72a70f808"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "a = 'hello world'\nb = 'hello world'\nc = 'hello' + ' ' + 'world'", "question": "What is the reliable way to compare strings for equality?", "options": ["Use is because CPython interns all string literals", "Use == because is compares identity; string interning is an implementation detail", "Use id(a) == id(b) for portability", "Both is and == are guaranteed equivalent for strings"], "correct_idx": 1, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "is-vs-equals-string-cache", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "The is operator checks object identity, not value equality. CPython interns some strings but this is not guaranteed and breaks for dynamically constructed strings. Always use == to test string equality.", "sources": ["PEP 8", "CPython source"], "iter": 2, "id": "b03bc80ae3bc"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "class Counter:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.count = 0\n    def increment(self):\n        self.count += 1\n\nc = Counter()", "question": "What would happen if __init__ omitted self?", "options": ["TypeError on instantiation because methods need self", "Nothing changes", "Counter() needs to be called as Counter.__init__()", "self.count would be auto-declared at class level"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "missing-self-arg", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Instance methods in Python receive the instance as the first positional argument, conventionally named self. Without it, calling Counter() raises TypeError. The fix is def __init__(self).", "sources": ["PEP 8", "Python docs"], "iter": 2, "id": "72b976a8fa90"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "def fetch(url):\n    if not url:\n        raise ValueError('empty')\n    raise ConnectionError('boom')\n\ntry:\n    fetch('')\nexcept ValueError:\n    print('value')\nexcept (ConnectionError, OSError):\n    print('handled')", "question": "What is the correct order of except handlers?", "options": ["Specific exceptions first, then broader tuples", "Broad tuples first, specific later", "Order does not matter", "Tuples cannot contain multiple types"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "except-order", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Except clauses are tested top-down and the first matching clause wins. List the most specific exceptions first, broader ones later. Otherwise specific handlers become unreachable dead code.", "sources": ["Python docs try statement"], "iter": 2, "id": "326bef549948"}
