{"lang": "python", "code": "import copy\noriginal = {'users': [{'name': 'Alice'}]}\ndeep = copy.deepcopy(original)\ndeep['users'][0]['name'] = 'Eve'\nprint(original['users'][0]['name'])", "question": "Why deepcopy here vs copy.copy?", "options": ["copy.copy is shallow; nested mutables would be shared with original", "Performance", "deepcopy is required for all dicts", "No difference"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "copy-vs-deepcopy-bug", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "copy.copy creates a new outer container but inner lists and dicts are still the same objects shared with the original. Mutating the inner dict would mutate original. Use copy.deepcopy when nested mutables must be independent.", "sources": ["Python docs copy module"], "iter": 2, "id": "b9729c065a3a"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "def add_node(value, tree=None):\n    if tree is None:\n        tree = []\n    tree.append(value)\n    return tree", "question": "Why is tree=None used instead of tree=[]?", "options": ["Mutable defaults are evaluated once at definition time and shared across calls; None sentinel avoids the bug", "No real difference", "Style preference only", "Required by linter rule"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "recursion-with-mutable-default", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Default argument values are evaluated once at function definition time and shared across all calls. Using None as a sentinel and constructing a fresh list inside the body avoids accumulating state across calls.", "sources": ["PEP 8", "Python FAQ"], "iter": 2, "id": "b418c24bf26f"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "class Animal:\n    def __init__(self, name):\n        self.name = name\n\nclass Dog(Animal):\n    def __init__(self, name, breed):\n        super().__init__(name)\n        self.breed = breed", "question": "What is the modern Python 3 idiom for calling super?", "options": ["super().__init__(name) without arguments", "super(Dog).__init__(name)", "super(Dog, name).__init__()", "Animal.__init__(name) directly"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "super-without-args", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "In Python 3, the zero-argument super().__init__(name) is the idiomatic form; the compiler rewrites it with the correct class cell and self. PEP 3135 introduced this convention to avoid repeating the class name.", "sources": ["PEP 3135", "Python docs super"], "iter": 2, "id": "3c8ec588f545"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "class Money:\n    def __init__(self, amount, currency):\n        self.amount = amount\n        self.currency = currency\n    def __repr__(self):\n        return f'Money({self.amount!r}, {self.currency!r})'\n    def __str__(self):\n        return f'{self.amount} {self.currency}'", "question": "Why define both __str__ and __repr__?", "options": ["__str__ is for display; __repr__ is for unambiguous representation (used in lists and REPL)", "Required by Python 3", "Cosmetic", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "str-vs-repr-bug", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "When a list is printed, its __repr__ calls repr() on each element, never str(). Defining only __str__ leaves the default object repr for list display. Implement both with distinct semantics.", "sources": ["Python docs data model"], "iter": 2, "id": "2a1bc261acc7"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "a = 1000\nb = 1000\nprint(a == b)\nprint(a is b)", "question": "Why might `a is b` be False even though `a == b` is True?", "options": ["CPython caches small ints in [-5, 256]; outside that range identity is not guaranteed", "Because 1000 is a prime", "Because is always compares string ids", "Because == is overloaded for int"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "ints-cached-vs-eq-pitfall", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "CPython pre-allocates and reuses integer objects in the range -5 to 256 as an optimization, so is coincidentally works for them. For larger ints, separate assignments may produce distinct objects. Always use == for value comparison; reserve is for identity checks like is None.", "sources": ["CPython source"], "iter": 2, "id": "2b80acf885ef"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "def average(numbers):\n    return sum(numbers) / len(numbers)\n\nprint(average([1, 2, 3, 4]))", "question": "What changed between Python 2 and 3 that makes this correct?", "options": ["/ performs true (float) division in Python 3; // would truncate", "Python 3 added len() function", "Python 3 made sum() handle floats", "No relevant change"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "division-int-vs-float", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "In Python 2, / performed integer (floor) division on ints, silently truncating averages. PEP 238 changed / to true division in Python 3. Code ported from Python 2 should be checked for places where // is actually wanted.", "sources": ["PEP 238"], "iter": 2, "id": "0f67e09a2d9d"}
