{"lang": "python", "code": "import re\ntext = '<b>hi</b><i>there</i>'\nm = re.search(r'<.+?>', text)\nprint(m.group())", "question": "Why use the non-greedy quantifier here?", "options": ["Greedy .+ would match across multiple tags up to the last >", "Greedy is not allowed", "Style only", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "regex-greedy-python", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "By default Python regex quantifiers are greedy, so .+ consumes as much as possible. To match a single tag, use the non-greedy form <.+?> or a stricter character class like <[^>]+>.", "sources": ["Python docs re"], "iter": 2, "id": "620e0c964211"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "from contextlib import suppress\n\ndef parse_user(s):\n    with suppress(ValueError):\n        name, age = s.split(',')\n        return {'name': name, 'age': int(age)}\n    return None", "question": "Why suppress only ValueError rather than Exception?", "options": ["suppress(Exception) hides programmer errors like KeyError; narrow scope catches only expected failures", "No difference", "ValueError is required", "suppress is decorative"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "contextlib-suppress-overuse", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "contextlib.suppress is meant to silence a specific, expected exception, not act as a catch-all. Listing only the exceptions you actually expect, such as ValueError for unpacking and int conversion, surfaces unrelated bugs.", "sources": ["Python docs"], "iter": 2, "id": "2429414b5b65"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "import hashlib\ndef hash_password(pw, salt):\n    return hashlib.pbkdf2_hmac('sha256', pw.encode(), salt, 100000)", "question": "Why use pbkdf2_hmac instead of hashlib.sha256 directly?", "options": ["pbkdf2 is intentionally slow with a configurable cost; KDFs resist offline brute-force", "Performance", "Required by stdlib", "sha256 is broken"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "weak-hash-for-password", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Password storage should use a slow, per-user-salted key derivation function such as pbkdf2, scrypt, bcrypt, or argon2. A plain sha256 is far too fast and lacks salting, making brute-force trivial.", "sources": ["OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet"], "iter": 2, "id": "861b6e45bf19"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "import threading\ncounter = 0\nlock = threading.Lock()\ndef worker():\n    global counter\n    for _ in range(100000):\n        with lock:\n            counter += 1", "question": "Why is the lock necessary?", "options": ["counter += 1 is not atomic across bytecodes; threads can race between LOAD/ADD/STORE", "Python is single-threaded", "Lock is decorative", "Performance"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "non-atomic-increment", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Even with the GIL, the compound operation counter += 1 is multiple bytecodes (LOAD/BINARY_ADD/STORE) and the interpreter can switch threads between them. A threading.Lock or atomic primitive is needed to protect the critical section.", "sources": ["Python docs threading"], "iter": 2, "id": "3e7193b9c73c"}
