{"lang": "javascript", "code": "function getPort(config) {\n  return config.port ?? 3000;\n}\nconsole.log(getPort({port: 0}));\nconsole.log(getPort({}));", "question": "Why ?? instead of ||?", "options": ["?? falls back only on null/undefined; || treats 0 and empty string as missing", "No difference", "Performance", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "nullish-vs-or-bug", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "|| treats all falsy values (0, '', false, NaN) as 'missing' and falls through to the default. ?? only falls through on null/undefined, preserving 0 and ''. For config with valid falsy values, use ??.", "sources": ["MDN Nullish coalescing"], "iter": 2, "id": "b5159804ef2a"}
