{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"sync/atomic\"\n)\n\ntype counter struct{ n int64 }\n\nfunc (c *counter) inc() { atomic.AddInt64(&c.n, 1) }\n\nfunc main() { c := &counter{}; c.inc(); fmt.Println(c.n) }", "question": "Why atomic.AddInt64 over a mutex for a counter?", "options": ["Single atomic RMW avoids the mutex's park/unpark and scheduler interaction", "Cosmetic", "Performance only", "Required by Go"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "atomic-vs-mutex-counter", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "For a single integer counter, atomic.AddInt64 avoids mutex queueing and cache-line ping-pong. Atomics are safe for int64 given alignment, which Go guarantees on 64-bit platforms.", "sources": ["sync/atomic docs"], "iter": 2, "id": "cdd5c23110ec"}
