{"lang": "sql", "code": "CREATE INDEX idx_orders_user_open ON orders (user_id) WHERE status = 'open';\nSELECT id, total FROM orders WHERE user_id = 42 AND status = 'open';", "question": "Why a partial index with WHERE status = 'open'?", "options": ["Dramatically smaller index; only covers the rows the workload actually reads", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "partial-index-where-clause", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "A partial index materializes only the rows matching its WHERE clause. The planner uses it whenever the query WHERE implies the index predicate.", "sources": ["PG docs partial indexes"], "iter": 2, "id": "8c547312bb74"}
{"lang": "sql", "code": "CREATE INDEX idx_meas_ts ON measurements USING brin (taken_at);", "question": "Why BRIN over BTREE for time-series?", "options": ["BRIN stores summary per block range; tiny size when data is naturally ordered", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "brin-vs-btree", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "BRIN works well when the indexed column is highly correlated with physical row order, typical for append-only time-series. Its on-disk size is tiny compared to a btree.", "sources": ["PG docs BRIN"], "iter": 2, "id": "8c88c0d1f467"}
{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT DISTINCT ON (customer_id) customer_id, order_id, total\nFROM orders\nORDER BY customer_id, total DESC;", "question": "Why DISTINCT ON over ROW_NUMBER()?", "options": ["Top-1-per-group is much shorter and often faster than the window-function pattern", "Required syntax", "Performance only", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "prefer-distinct-on-vs-window", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "DISTINCT ON picks the first row per distinct group given an ORDER BY. For top-1 per group it is shorter than the ROW_NUMBER + subquery pattern.", "sources": ["PG docs SELECT"], "iter": 2, "id": "fceda96c9570"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "import hashlib\n\ndef store_password(password: str) -> str:\n    salt = b\"static_salt_v1\"\n    h = hashlib.md5(salt + password.encode())\n    return h.hexdigest()", "question": "What is the most serious security flaw in this password storage routine?", "options": ["Using a fast unsalted-equivalent hash (MD5) with a hardcoded salt instead of a slow KDF with a per-user random salt", "The function signatures omit a return-type annotation", "The salt should be encoded as utf-8 instead of bytes", "hashlib.md5 should be called with usedforsecurity=False"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "password-hashing-kdf", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Password storage requires a memory-hard or iterated KDF (bcrypt/scrypt/argon2/PBKDF2) with a unique random per-user salt. MD5 is GPU-cracking-friendly and a global static salt defeats salt purpose.", "sources": ["OWASP ASVS V2.4"], "iter": 3, "id": "c148ff9a7592"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET\n\ndef count_items(xml_blob: str) -> int:\n    root = ET.fromstring(xml_blob)\n    return len(root.findall('.//item'))", "question": "What untrusted-input risk does this XML parser expose?", "options": ["XXE and billion-laughs entity expansion attacks; stdlib ElementTree is documented as unsafe on untrusted XML", "ET.fromstring leaks file descriptors", "findall with .//item is O(n^2)", "The function should use ET.parse instead"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "xxe-entity-expansion", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Untrusted XML must be parsed with a hardened parser (defusedxml) because entity expansion and external entity attacks can exfiltrate files or exhaust memory. Stock ElementTree is documented as not secure against maliciously constructed data.", "sources": ["Python docs xml security"], "iter": 3, "id": "b99042bf15d3"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "import secrets\n\ndef compare(a: str, b: str) -> bool:\n    return secrets.compare_digest(a, b)", "question": "Why secrets.compare_digest over plain ==?", "options": ["compare_digest is constant-time; == short-circuits and leaks timing info via response latency", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "timing-attack-constant-time", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Secret comparison must be constant-time so attackers cannot infer prefix matches from response latency. Python == on str returns at the first mismatch leaking byte-by-byte information. secrets.compare_digest is the documented constant-time primitive.", "sources": ["Python secrets docs"], "iter": 3, "id": "f67e5afbed8d"}
{"lang": "javascript", "code": "function parseAmounts(rows) {\n  const totals = {};\n  for (const r of rows) {\n    totals[r.bucket] = (totals[r.bucket] || 0) + parseInt(r.amount, 10);\n  }\n  return totals;\n}", "question": "Why pass 10 as the second argument to parseInt?", "options": ["Avoid implementation-dependent parsing of 0x or octal prefixes; always specify radix", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "No reason"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "parseint-radix", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "The defensive-coding principle be explicit about parsing: parseInt second argument defaults are historically implementation-dependent. Always pass 10 so user data like 08 or 0x10 cannot silently change the total.", "sources": ["MDN parseInt"], "iter": 3, "id": "7417708d1302"}
{"lang": "javascript", "code": "async function fetchAll(ids, load) {\n  return Promise.all(ids.map(id => load(id)));\n}", "question": "Why Promise.all over sequential await?", "options": ["Independent I/O can run in parallel; sequential await multiplies total latency", "Performance only", "Required syntax", "Cosmetic"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "sequential-await-antipattern", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "The do not await in a loop for independent work principle: each iteration blocks on the previous, turning N parallelizable RTTs into N serial ones. Promise.all lets the event loop dispatch them concurrently.", "sources": ["MDN Promise.all"], "iter": 3, "id": "34013c401557"}
{"lang": "javascript", "code": "function deepFreeze(obj) {\n  Object.freeze(obj);\n  for (const k of Reflect.ownKeys(obj)) {\n    const v = obj[k];\n    if (v && typeof v === 'object') {\n      deepFreeze(v);\n    }\n  }\n  return obj;\n}", "question": "Why Reflect.ownKeys vs Object.keys for deep freeze?", "options": ["Object.keys skips non-enumerable and Symbol keys; Reflect.ownKeys enumerates ALL own properties", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "No reason"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "reflect-ownkeys", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "Deep operations must enumerate ALL own properties. Object.keys only returns enumerable string keys, missing Symbols and non-enumerable descriptors. Reflect.ownKeys is the correct primitive for a truly deep freeze.", "sources": ["MDN Reflect.ownKeys"], "iter": 3, "id": "536592319054"}
{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport \"sync\"\n\nfunc fanout(items []int, work func(int) int) []int {\n\tvar wg sync.WaitGroup\n\tout := make([]int, len(items))\n\tfor i, v := range items {\n\t\twg.Add(1)\n\t\tgo func(i, v int) {\n\t\t\tdefer wg.Done()\n\t\t\tout[i] = work(v)\n\t\t}(i, v)\n\t}\n\twg.Wait()\n\treturn out\n}", "question": "Why pass i and v as parameters to the goroutine?", "options": ["Avoid the pre-Go-1.22 loop-var capture race and provide a unique slot per goroutine", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "loopvar-capture", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "Pre-1.22 the loop variable is reused across iterations, so goroutines may all see the last value. Passing as parameters captures by value. Writing into a pre-sized slice via index avoids concurrent append races.", "sources": ["Go 1.22 release notes"], "iter": 3, "id": "52dddc618b87"}
{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport (\n\t\"context\"\n\t\"time\"\n)\n\nfunc withDeadline(parent context.Context, work func(context.Context) error) error {\n\tctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(parent, 2*time.Second)\n\tdefer cancel()\n\treturn work(ctx)\n}", "question": "Why defer cancel()?", "options": ["context.WithTimeout returns a cancel func that must be called to release the timer and child contexts", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "context-cancel", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Always call cancel even on the success path. Dropping the cancel keeps the internal timer goroutine and child contexts alive until the parent finishes, which leaks resources and trips go vet lostcancel check.", "sources": ["context docs"], "iter": 3, "id": "136b5c5eb416"}
{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport \"sync\"\n\ntype Cache struct {\n\tmu sync.RWMutex\n\tm  map[string]int\n}\n\nfunc (c *Cache) Inc(k string) {\n\tc.mu.Lock()\n\tdefer c.mu.Unlock()\n\tc.m[k]++\n}", "question": "Why Lock() and not RLock() in Inc?", "options": ["Writing requires exclusive lock; RLock allows concurrent readers and races on map writes", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "rwmutex-write", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "RLock allows many concurrent readers but no writers. Writing under RLock is a data race and Go map detects concurrent writes at runtime and panics. Inc must call mu.Lock().", "sources": ["sync.RWMutex docs"], "iter": 3, "id": "6569af7b541c"}
{"lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn sum_squares(xs: &[i32]) -> i64 {\n    xs.iter().map(|&x| (x as i64) * (x as i64)).sum()\n}", "question": "Why &[i32] and iter().map().sum()?", "options": ["Slice param is least restrictive; iterators elide bounds checks and often vectorize", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "slice-and-iter", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Take the least restrictive parameter and prefer iterator combinators because the optimizer can prove bounds and emit branchless code. Manual index loops frequently retain bounds checks LLVM cannot eliminate.", "sources": ["Rust Performance Book"], "iter": 3, "id": "f062ffd0d059"}
{"lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn join_names(names: &[&str]) -> String {\n    names.join(\", \")\n}", "question": "Why use slice::join over a manual loop?", "options": ["join allocates once with the right capacity, avoiding O(n^2) per-iteration realloc", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "quadratic-string-concat", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Avoid hidden quadratic work in loops: Rust Add for String takes self by value and produces a new String, so each iteration copies the growing buffer. push_str amortizes to O(n), and [&str]::join allocates exactly once.", "sources": ["Rust docs"], "iter": 3, "id": "074b9d6c55f5"}
{"lang": "rust", "code": "use std::collections::HashMap;\n\npub fn count_words(text: &str) -> HashMap<String, u32> {\n    let mut m: HashMap<String, u32> = HashMap::new();\n    for w in text.split_whitespace() {\n        if let Some(v) = m.get_mut(w) { *v += 1; } else { m.insert(w.to_string(), 1); }\n    }\n    m\n}", "question": "Why get_mut before entry?", "options": ["Avoid allocating a String key on hits; only allocate on first insert", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required by Rust"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "entry-allocates-on-hit", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "Do not allocate on the hot path. HashMap entry takes an owned key, so to_string runs even when the word is already a key. A get_mut fast-path lets the allocation happen only on first insert.", "sources": ["HashMap docs"], "iter": 3, "id": "c36b12bf6959"}
{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, name\nFROM products\nWHERE sku = 'AB-1234'\n  AND created_at >= '2026-05-19'\n  AND created_at <  '2026-05-20';", "question": "Why a half-open date range vs created_at::date = '2026-05-19'?", "options": ["Casting an indexed column to date is non-sargable; half-open range keeps the b-tree usable", "Cosmetic", "Performance only", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "sargability-date-cast", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Wrapping an indexed column in a function (CAST to date) hides it from the b-tree, so the planner cannot use the index. Rewriting to a half-open range restores index usability.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL docs"], "iter": 3, "id": "623631e2b8e3"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "import threading\n\ncounter = 0\nlock = threading.Lock()\n\ndef worker(n):\n    global counter\n    for _ in range(n):\n        with lock:\n            counter += 1", "question": "Why is `with lock:` the idiomatic critical section here?", "options": ["counter += 1 is non-atomic at the bytecode level; the lock serializes it correctly", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "critical-section", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Once the lock is held, the read-modify-write is serialized. Keep critical sections small AND readable - the idiomatic counter += 1 inside the with-block is both correct and concise. Without the lock the GIL does NOT guarantee atomicity of += across bytecodes.", "sources": ["Python threading docs"], "iter": 4, "id": "7e612b246576"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "import asyncio\n\nasync def fetch(i):\n    await asyncio.sleep(0.01)\n    return i\n\nasync def main(items):\n    return await asyncio.gather(*[fetch(i) for i in items])", "question": "Why asyncio.gather over `for i in items: await fetch(i)`?", "options": ["Sequential await serializes independent I/O; gather fan-outs and runs concurrently", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "await-in-loop", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Each await suspends until that one fetch finishes, so the loop runs sequentially despite being async. Awaiting in a loop is the async equivalent of a synchronous call. Fan out with asyncio.gather when tasks are independent.", "sources": ["asyncio docs"], "iter": 4, "id": "b0bacdbe1451"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "from concurrent.futures import ProcessPoolExecutor\n\ndef process(x):\n    return x * x\n\ndef run(items):\n    with ProcessPoolExecutor(max_workers=4) as ex:\n        return list(ex.map(process, items, chunksize=100))", "question": "Why ProcessPoolExecutor + chunksize for CPU-bound work?", "options": ["Threads are GIL-bound for CPU work; processes parallelize and chunksize amortizes IPC", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "process-pool-cpu", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "For pure-Python CPU work the GIL serializes execution, so threads add overhead without speedup. ProcessPoolExecutor with chunksize is the correct fan-out: match the executor to the workload and pass chunksize for short tasks to amortize IPC.", "sources": ["concurrent.futures docs"], "iter": 4, "id": "fc552cd27ee6"}
{"lang": "javascript", "code": "function greet(name) {\n  if (name == null) {\n    return 'hello, stranger';\n  }\n  const msg = `hello, ${name}`;\n  return msg;\n}", "question": "Why const + template literal here?", "options": ["const expresses immutability; template literal is more readable than +", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required by ES2015"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "var-vs-let-template-literal", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Modern JS style guides require const/let over var for block scoping, and prefer template literals over + concatenation. The == null check is idiomatic for null-or-undefined and should not be flagged.", "sources": ["Airbnb JS style guide"], "iter": 4, "id": "102fd1cbfea9"}
{"lang": "javascript", "code": "const users = [{id:1,name:'a'},{id:2,name:'b'}];\n\nfunction findUser(id) {\n  return users.find(u => u.id === id);\n}", "question": "Why Array.find vs forEach with external accumulator?", "options": ["find short-circuits at the first match and avoids mutation", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "forEach-vs-find", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "forEach cannot be broken out of and forces an external mutable variable. Array.prototype.find expresses intent directly and stops at the first match. Choose the array method whose semantics match the intent.", "sources": ["MDN Array.find"], "iter": 4, "id": "23eef26752d0"}
