{"lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn average(xs: &[i32]) -> Option<i64> {\n    if xs.is_empty() { return None; }\n    let sum: i64 = xs.iter().map(|&x| x as i64).sum();\n    Some(sum / xs.len() as i64)\n}", "question": "Why return Option and accumulate in i64?", "options": ["Empty slice case represented as None; widening prevents i32 overflow", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required by Rust"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "int-overflow-empty", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Integer division by zero panics, and i32 sum can panic on overflow in debug. For arithmetic over untrusted inputs, prefer checked/saturating/wrapping explicitly or widen the accumulator.", "sources": ["Rust reference"], "iter": 4, "id": "30c15f8f3d3e"}
{"lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn last<T: Clone>(v: &[T]) -> Option<T> {\n    v.last().cloned()\n}", "question": "Why &[T] and Option return?", "options": ["Slice borrow avoids forcing ownership; Option expresses empty case", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required by Rust"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "by-value-param", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Taking Vec by value forces a move and prevents reuse. The function panics on empty input and consumes the vector for a single read. fn last(v: &[T]) -> Option<T> expresses fallibility and minimal ownership.", "sources": ["Rust API Guidelines"], "iter": 4, "id": "3f24233df9f1"}
{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT u.id, u.name, o.total\nFROM users u\nLEFT JOIN orders o ON o.user_id = u.id AND o.status = 'shipped'\nWHERE u.created_at >= '2026-01-01';", "question": "Why put o.status = 'shipped' in ON, not WHERE?", "options": ["WHERE on a nullable right-side column converts LEFT JOIN into INNER JOIN", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "left-join-where", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Filtering a nullable right-side column in WHERE drops every unmatched row, silently turning LEFT JOIN into INNER. Predicates on the outer side of an outer join belong in the ON clause.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL docs"], "iter": 4, "id": "e1c51e95a8f8"}
{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT product_id, COUNT(*) AS sales\nFROM order_items\nWHERE created_at >= '2026-01-01' AND created_at < '2027-01-01'\nGROUP BY product_id\nORDER BY sales DESC\nLIMIT 10;", "question": "Why a half-open range instead of YEAR(created_at) = 2026?", "options": ["YEAR() wraps the column making it non-sargable; range keeps the index usable", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "sargable", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Applying a function to an indexed column hides it from the planner and forces a full scan. A half-open range predicate keeps the index usable. Keep predicates sargable - transform the literal, never the column.", "sources": ["Use The Index Luke"], "iter": 4, "id": "60a4345e2496"}
{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, total\nFROM events\nWHERE customer_id IN (\n  SELECT id FROM customers WHERE country = 'VN'\n)\nORDER BY created_at DESC\nLIMIT 100;", "question": "Why project columns explicitly and consider a covering index?", "options": ["SELECT * blocks index-only scans; covering index aligned with filter+sort handles top-N efficiently", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "covering-index", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "SELECT * pulls every column, preventing index-only scans and inflating sort memory. Restricting projection and adding a covering composite index on (customer_id, created_at DESC) lets the planner walk the index in order and stop after LIMIT.", "sources": ["PG docs index-only scans"], "iter": 4, "id": "205224c62c0b"}
