{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport (\n\t\"database/sql\"\n)\n\nfunc getUser(db *sql.DB, name string) (string, error) {\n\tvar email string\n\terr := db.QueryRow(\"SELECT email FROM users WHERE name = ?\", name).Scan(&email)\n\treturn email, err\n}", "question": "Why parameterized query vs string formatting?", "options": ["Defends against SQL injection by separating data from code", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "sql-injection", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "User-controlled input must never be interpolated into SQL text. Parameterized queries with placeholders let the driver handle escaping, preserving the value/code boundary. This is the canonical defense against CWE-89 injection vulnerabilities.", "sources": ["OWASP A03"], "iter": 5, "id": "688413916ddb"}
