{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT department, AVG(salary) AS avg_sal\nFROM employees\nWHERE salary IS NOT NULL\nGROUP BY department\nHAVING AVG(salary) > 50000;", "question": "Why filter NULL salaries before AVG?", "options": ["AVG skips NULL by default; explicit filter documents intent and excludes all-NULL groups", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "null-in-aggregate", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Aggregate functions like AVG ignore NULL inputs and a customer with all-NULL salaries yields AVG = NULL which fails the predicate. Explicitly handling NULL in aggregates with COALESCE or filtering upfront makes the contract clear to readers.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL aggregate docs"], "iter": 5, "id": "f868011cd53c"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "import sqlite3\n\ndef get_user(conn, username):\n    cur = conn.cursor()\n    cur.execute('SELECT id, email FROM users WHERE name = ?', (username,))\n    return cur.fetchone()", "question": "Why parameter binding here?", "options": ["Defends against SQL injection by escaping at driver level", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "sql-injection", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "String concatenation of untrusted input into SQL statements is a textbook injection vector. DB-API parameter substitution delegates escaping to the driver and preserves the value/code boundary, a foundational defense against CWE-89 vulnerabilities.", "sources": ["CWE-89"], "iter": 6, "id": "b93587102a42"}
{"lang": "javascript", "code": "function sumPositives(arr) {\n  let total = 0;\n  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {\n    if (arr[i] > 0) total += arr[i];\n  }\n  return total;\n}", "question": "Why i < arr.length not i <= arr.length?", "options": ["Indices run 0..length-1; off-by-one would read undefined", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "off-by-one", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Array indices run from 0 to length-1, so the terminating condition must be i < arr.length. Reading arr[arr.length] yields undefined which would poison the sum. The fence-post principle: the number of valid indices equals length, not length+1.", "sources": ["MDN Array.length"], "iter": 6, "id": "d07041d074be"}
