{"lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn build_path(parts: &[&str]) -> String {\n    let mut s = String::with_capacity(parts.iter().map(|p| p.len() + 1).sum());\n    for (i, p) in parts.iter().enumerate() {\n        if i > 0 { s.push('/'); }\n        s.push_str(p);\n    }\n    s\n}", "question": "Why pre-size with capacity?", "options": ["Avoids repeated reallocation during push_str", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "string-prealloc", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Building a string with repeated push_str may reallocate. with_capacity pre-sizes the buffer so push_str is amortized O(1). The principle of avoiding hidden quadratic work applies here.", "sources": ["Rust Performance Book"], "iter": 6, "id": "08c9d357ed46"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "def count_pairs(nums, target):\n    counts = {}\n    pairs = 0\n    for n in nums:\n        pairs += counts.get(target - n, 0)\n        counts[n] = counts.get(n, 0) + 1\n    return pairs", "question": "Why one-pass hash over nested loop?", "options": ["O(n) with hash lookups vs O(n^2) nested scan", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "algorithmic-complexity", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Counting complementary pairs can be done in linear time by walking once and looking up target-x in a hash map. This is the classic two-sum frequency principle: trade O(n) memory for O(n) time instead of O(n^2).", "sources": ["CLRS hashing"], "iter": 7, "id": "bb38b176cb4b"}
