{"lang": "javascript", "code": "function sumNested(arr) {\n  let total = 0;\n  for (let i = 0, n = arr.length; i < n; i++) {\n    const inner = arr[i];\n    for (let j = 0, m = inner.length; j < m; j++) {\n      total += inner[j];\n    }\n  }\n  return total;\n}", "question": "Why hoist arr[i] and arr[i].length into locals?", "options": ["Avoids repeated property reads the JIT cannot always elide", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "property-hoist", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Each arr[i] and arr[i].length is a separate property access the JIT must re-resolve. Hoisting them into locals enables register allocation and skips repeated load instructions. This is loop-invariant code motion applied manually.", "sources": ["V8 hidden classes"], "iter": 8, "id": "16bd537af70e"}
{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport \"fmt\"\n\nfunc contains(m map[string]int, key string) (int, bool) {\n\tv, ok := m[key]\n\treturn v, ok\n}\n\nfunc main() { fmt.Println(contains(map[string]int{\"a\": 0}, \"a\")) }", "question": "Why the comma-ok pattern?", "options": ["Distinguishes absence from a stored zero value", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "zero-value-conflation", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "In Go missing keys return the zero value, so a stored 0 is indistinguishable from absence using simple indexing. The idiomatic check is the comma-ok form: distinguishing zero from absent is essential for correctness.", "sources": ["Go spec map"], "iter": 8, "id": "fece3c663981"}
{"lang": "rust", "code": "use std::sync::Mutex;\nuse std::thread;\n\npub fn run() {\n    let m = Mutex::new(0);\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        for _ in 0..4 {\n            s.spawn(|| {\n                *m.lock().unwrap() += 1;\n            });\n        }\n    });\n}", "question": "Why thread::scope?", "options": ["Borrowed references shared with child threads are safe because scope guarantees join before drop", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "scoped-threads", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "thread::scope lets borrowed references be shared with child threads safely because the scope guarantees they join before m is dropped. Arc is required only for static spawning; here Mutex provides the necessary acquire/release fences.", "sources": ["std::thread::scope"], "iter": 8, "id": "767df9c3b182"}
{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT product_id, SUM(qty) AS total\nFROM order_items\nGROUP BY product_id\nHAVING SUM(qty) > 100;", "question": "Why HAVING vs WHERE for the aggregate filter?", "options": ["WHERE runs before GROUP BY and cannot see aggregates; HAVING runs after", "Cosmetic", "Performance", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "where-vs-having", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "WHERE is evaluated before GROUP BY, so it cannot see aggregates or their aliases. Aggregate predicates belong in HAVING, reflecting the canonical logical query processing order: FROM > WHERE > GROUP BY > HAVING > SELECT.", "sources": ["SQL standard"], "iter": 8, "id": "49f6d0dd9243"}
