{"lang": "javascript", "code": "async function fetchAll(urls) {\n  return Promise.all(urls.map(u => fetch(u).then(r => r.json())));\n}", "question": "Why Promise.all over for-loop with await?", "options": ["Independent fetches run concurrently instead of sequentially", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "sequential-await", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Each await suspends the loop until the current request resolves, so N requests take roughly N times latency instead of max latency. Promise.all dispatches concurrently using the structured-concurrency fan-out principle.", "sources": ["MDN Promise.all"], "iter": 9, "id": "84043c11805c"}
{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport \"fmt\"\n\nfunc divide(a, b int) (int, error) {\n\tif b == 0 {\n\t\treturn 0, fmt.Errorf(\"divide by zero\")\n\t}\n\treturn a / b, nil\n}\n\nfunc main() { fmt.Println(divide(10, 0)) }", "question": "Why the guard before division?", "options": ["Integer division by zero panics; guard must precede the operation", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "guard-clause-ordering", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Integer division by zero in Go triggers a runtime panic, so a / b must never execute when b is 0. The guard clause must precede the operation it protects - the precondition-before-use principle universal to defensive programming.", "sources": ["Go spec integer ops"], "iter": 9, "id": "894065041440"}
