{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT u.id, u.name, agg.order_count, agg.total\nFROM users u\nLEFT JOIN (\n  SELECT user_id, COUNT(*) AS order_count, SUM(amount) AS total\n  FROM orders\n  GROUP BY user_id\n) agg ON agg.user_id = u.id\nWHERE u.active = TRUE\nORDER BY agg.total DESC NULLS LAST\nLIMIT 50;", "question": "Why join an aggregated CTE over correlated subqueries?", "options": ["Single pass over orders vs N-times subquery execution", "Performance only", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "correlated-subquery", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Each correlated scalar subquery executes per outer row, producing an N x M pattern. A single LEFT JOIN with GROUP BY scans orders just once and lets the planner use a hash or merge aggregate.", "sources": ["PostgreSQL query planner"], "iter": 9, "id": "806b2112f25a"}
