{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport \"fmt\"\n\nfunc firstNonEmpty(ss []string) (string, bool) {\n\tfor _, s := range ss {\n\t\tif s != \"\" {\n\t\t\treturn s, true\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn \"\", false\n}\n\nfunc main() { fmt.Println(firstNonEmpty(nil)) }", "question": "Why return (string, bool) here?", "options": ["Distinguishes no-element from found-empty, avoids zero-value conflation", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "bug", "subtopic": "api-design", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Ranging over a nil slice yields zero iterations, so the function may return the zero value empty string meaning either no-element or found-empty. The idiomatic fix returns (string, bool) following Go comma-ok pattern.", "sources": ["Effective Go"], "iter": 10, "id": "08ab128a49f0"}
{"lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn split_in_half(s: &str) -> (&str, &str) {\n    let target = s.len() / 2;\n    let mut mid = target;\n    while mid > 0 && !s.is_char_boundary(mid) { mid -= 1; }\n    s.split_at(mid)\n}", "question": "Why is_char_boundary scan?", "options": ["Plain byte-half may land mid-codepoint; align to UTF-8 char boundary", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "utf8-boundary", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "Rust str indexing is in bytes but enforces char-boundary alignment. For multi-byte strings, byte length divided by 2 may fall between bytes of a single char, panicking on slice. is_char_boundary finds a safe split point.", "sources": ["Rust str docs"], "iter": 10, "id": "66439da2fdff"}
{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT *\nFROM events\nWHERE created_at >= '2026-05-20'\n  AND created_at <  '2026-05-21'\n  AND status = 'OK'\nORDER BY created_at DESC;", "question": "Why a half-open range over DATE(created_at) = '2026-05-20'?", "options": ["DATE() wraps the column making it non-sargable; range form keeps the index usable", "Cosmetic", "Performance only", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "perf", "subtopic": "sargability", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Applying a function to an indexed column forces a full scan. The optimizer cannot translate function output back into an index range. Rewriting as a half-open range restores sargability.", "sources": ["Use The Index Luke"], "iter": 10, "id": "95138beccbfe"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "def median(nums):\n    if not nums: return None\n    s = sorted(nums)\n    n = len(s)\n    mid = n // 2\n    if n % 2:\n        return s[mid]\n    return (s[mid-1] + s[mid]) / 2", "question": "Why average two middle values for even-length input?", "options": ["Median of even-length data is the mean of the two central order statistics", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "median-even-length", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "The mathematical median of an even-length sample is the mean of the two central order statistics, not a single index. Returning s[n//2] biases the result upward by one position and violates the median symmetry property.", "sources": ["wikipedia median"], "iter": 11, "id": "44f2720419b6"}
{"lang": "javascript", "code": "const path = require('path');\nfunction safePath(root, name) {\n  const requested = path.resolve(root, name);\n  if (!requested.startsWith(root + path.sep)) {\n    throw new Error('outside root');\n  }\n  return requested;\n}", "question": "Why resolve + prefix check?", "options": ["Prevents path traversal via .. escape; canonicalize then verify within root", "Cosmetic", "Performance", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "path-traversal", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Concatenating untrusted input into a filesystem path lets an attacker submit dot-dot sequences and escape the intended directory. Canonicalize via path.resolve then verify the result starts with the allowed root (CWE-22).", "sources": ["CWE-22"], "iter": 11, "id": "449a0618cbca"}
{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport (\n\t\"context\"\n\t\"sync\"\n)\n\nfunc Fetch(ctx context.Context, urls []string, fetch func(string) string) []string {\n\tout := make(chan string, len(urls))\n\tvar wg sync.WaitGroup\n\tfor _, u := range urls {\n\t\twg.Add(1)\n\t\tgo func(u string) {\n\t\t\tdefer wg.Done()\n\t\t\tout <- fetch(u)\n\t\t}(u)\n\t}\n\twg.Wait()\n\tclose(out)\n\tres := []string{}\n\tfor s := range out {\n\t\tres = append(res, s)\n\t}\n\treturn res\n}", "question": "Why buffer the channel to len(urls)?", "options": ["Prevents goroutine leak when caller returns early without draining", "Cosmetic", "Performance", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "goroutine-leak", "difficulty": "hard", "explain": "On early return goroutines block forever on an unbuffered channel with no receiver, leaking until process exit. Buffering to len(urls) lets them complete without a receiver waiting.", "sources": ["Dave Cheney never start goroutine"], "iter": 11, "id": "f929644c6820"}
{"lang": "rust", "code": "use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};\n\npub struct Counter(Arc<Mutex<u64>>);\n\nimpl Counter {\n    pub fn inc(&self) {\n        let mut g = self.0.lock().unwrap();\n        *g += 1;\n    }\n}", "question": "Why Arc<Mutex<u64>> rather than Arc<u64>?", "options": ["Arc gives shared but immutable access; Mutex adds interior mutability", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "interior-mutability", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Arc gives shared ownership but only immutable access to its contents, enforcing aliasing-XOR-mutability across threads. To mutate shared state safely, wrap in an atomic type or a Mutex; bare Arc<u64> is read-only.", "sources": ["Arc docs"], "iter": 11, "id": "8e0143bff3a1"}
{"lang": "sql", "code": "SELECT id, name, email\nFROM users\nWHERE status = 'active'\n  AND created_at > '2025-01-01'\nORDER BY name;", "question": "Why ORDER BY name (column reference) over ORDER BY 2 (ordinal)?", "options": ["Ordinal breaks silently if the SELECT list is reordered; column name is refactor-safe", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "style", "subtopic": "ordinal-order-by", "difficulty": "easy", "explain": "Positional ORDER BY couples sort order to column position, so any later reordering of the SELECT list silently changes results. Always sort by explicit column name or alias to make intent locally readable.", "sources": ["sqlstyle.guide"], "iter": 11, "id": "7ff0a4ae33ee"}
{"lang": "python", "code": "import hashlib, os\nfrom hashlib import pbkdf2_hmac\n\ndef hash_password(pw: str):\n    salt = os.urandom(16)\n    digest = pbkdf2_hmac('sha256', pw.encode(), salt, 100000)\n    return salt, digest", "question": "Why pbkdf2_hmac with 100k iterations and 16-byte salt?", "options": ["Slow KDF with per-user salt resists offline cracking", "Performance", "Cosmetic", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "security", "subtopic": "password-hashing", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Password storage requires a deliberately slow, memory-hard or iterated KDF with a unique random per-user salt of adequate length. Fast hashes like MD5 are GPU-trivial to brute force.", "sources": ["OWASP Password Storage"], "iter": 12, "id": "bf217c776da2"}
