{"lang": "go", "code": "package main\n\nimport (\n\t\"context\"\n\t\"sync\"\n)\n\nfunc Sum(ctx context.Context, nums []int) int {\n\tvar mu sync.Mutex\n\ttotal := 0\n\tvar wg sync.WaitGroup\n\tfor _, n := range nums {\n\t\twg.Add(1)\n\t\tgo func(n int) {\n\t\t\tdefer wg.Done()\n\t\t\tmu.Lock()\n\t\t\ttotal += n\n\t\t\tmu.Unlock()\n\t\t}(n)\n\t}\n\twg.Wait()\n\treturn total\n}", "question": "Why pass n explicitly plus use a Mutex on total?", "options": ["Capture-by-value avoids loop-var race; Mutex serializes total updates", "Cosmetic", "Performance", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "concurrency", "subtopic": "data-race", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "Pre-1.22 the loop variable is shared across iterations so goroutines may all see the last value. Passing n as parameter captures by value. Concurrent unsynchronized writes to total are also a data race the race detector flags.", "sources": ["Go memory model"], "iter": 12, "id": "b45e27d7f094"}
{"lang": "rust", "code": "pub fn first_char(s: &str) -> Option<char> {\n    s.chars().next()\n}", "question": "Why chars().next() returning Option vs byte slice + unwrap?", "options": ["Byte slicing may panic on UTF-8 boundary; chars iterates codepoints safely and Option expresses empty input", "Cosmetic", "Performance", "Required syntax"], "correct_idx": 0, "topic": "edge", "subtopic": "utf8-boundary", "difficulty": "med", "explain": "&str slicing uses byte offsets and panics if bounds are not on UTF-8 char boundaries. The idiomatic char-safe API is chars().next, returning Option to express empty input.", "sources": ["Rust str docs"], "iter": 12, "id": "f5cf5865ce0b"}
